This paper is about unsupervised text style transfer, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). The use of language models as discriminators suggests that the paper is likely to be related to deep learning techniques in NLP, which are often categorized under cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also mentions the use of back-propagation, which is a common optimization technique in machine learning, suggesting that the paper may also be related to machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper proposes a new technique for training the generator, which involves minimizing the negative log likelihood of generated sentences, suggesting that the paper may also be related to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also mentions the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) as discriminators, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV), suggesting that the paper may also be related to computer vision techniques. Finally, the paper mentions the use of stable training techniques, which may be related to neural engineering (cs.NE).
